LEVEL: CERTIFIED GOLDEN
FILE: /lenses/computational/MetaLens_Phase_Gradient.opt

WHAT IS THIS FILE
The certified optical model for a flat meta-lens that uses sub-wavelength
nanostructures to impart a phase gradient, focusing light without bulk glass.
It defines the phase profile φ(r) = (2π/λ)(f – √(r² + f²)) and the
achromatic meta-lens condition for broadband focusing.

WHY IT EXISTS
Meta-lenses are entering commercial production (2026). They promise wafer-thin
cameras. GIOP must provide the normative equations so that imaging pipelines
can simulate and correct the unique aberrations of meta-lenses.

HOW IT WORKS
1. Principle:
   A dielectric metasurface consists of an array of nanofins (TiO₂, GaN, etc.)
   on a substrate. Each nanofin acts as a waveguide; its geometry (width,
   length, rotation) controls the phase delay imparted to transmitted light.

2. Required phase profile for a focusing lens:
   φ(r,λ) = (2π/λ) (f(λ) – √(r² + f(λ)²))
   where r is radial distance from the optical axis, λ is wavelength in the
   medium, and f(λ) is the design focal length at that wavelength.

3. Chromatic dispersion:
   For a single-material meta-lens, f(λ) ∝ 1/λ. This leads to strong chromatic
   focal shift: Δf/f ≈ Δλ/λ.
   Achromatic metalenses correct this by using multiple nanofin geometries
   (dispersion engineering). The condition for an achromatic doublet meta-lens:
     φ(r,λ_1) = φ(r,λ_2) = φ(r,λ_3)  (for RGB)
   achieved by combining two meta-layers of different materials or by
   multiplexing nanopillar widths.

4. Efficiency:
   Focusing efficiency η = power in focused spot / incident power.
   Current state (2026): η > 80% for NA < 0.2, >60% for NA up to 0.5.
   Efficiency drops at large angles due to impedance mismatch.

5. Point spread function (PSF) and MTF:
   The complex amplitude at the image plane is the Fourier transform of the
   metasurface phase profile. The PSF is |FT{exp(j φ(r))}|².
   MTF is the modulus of the optical transfer function (OTF), computed via
   autocorrelation of the pupil function.

6. Aberrations:
   - Spherical aberration: negligible when phase profile is exact.
   - Coma and astigmatism: appear at field angles > 5°; scale with angle.
   - Field curvature: strong; Petzval sum is non-zero because the meta-lens
     is flat.
   These aberrations are corrected by applying a space-variant deconvolution
   or by designing a metasurface with field-dependent phase.

WHERE IT IS DEPLOYED
- Smartphone cameras (2026+: under-display cameras)
- AR/MR glasses (ultra-thin combiners)
- Medical endoscopes
GIOP uses this model to build IDTs for meta-lens cameras.

WHO USES IT
L1 Architects specifying next-gen sensors; L2 Engineers building software
correction for meta-lens aberrations.

WHAT PROBLEM IT SOLVES
Provides the first open standard for meta-lens optical characterization,
enabling software to correct strong chromatic focal shift and field curvature
that differ fundamentally from refractive lenses. Allows GIOP pipelines to
ingest images from wafer-thin cameras.

